{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586913"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.05,0.04,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2018"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19017"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis is an immune-mediated kidney injury that occurs following infection with certain strains of streptococcal bacteria. The condition typically develops one to three weeks after the initial infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most useful for confirming recent streptococcal infection in suspected post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-streptolysin O titre","Complement C4 level","Rheumatoid factor","Urine culture","von Willebrand factor"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-streptolysin O titre\u003C/strong\u003E is the most useful serological test for confirming recent streptococcal infection. It measures antibodies against streptolysin O, a toxin produced by group A beta-haemolytic streptococci.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplement C4 level\u003C/strong\u003E is typically normal in post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, while C3 is characteristically low. \u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful in diagnosing post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis as it is associated with autoimmune conditions like rheumatoid arthritis. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine culture\u003C/strong\u003E would not show the causative streptococcal infection as it occurred weeks earlier. \u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand factor\u003C/strong\u003E is a marker of endothelial injury but is not specific for post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-streptolysin O (ASO) titres help diagnose post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis by detecting previous streptococcal infection","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis typically develops 1-3 weeks after streptococcal infection","Complement C3 levels are typically low in acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis"],"references":["Rawla P, Padala SA, Ludhwani D. Poststreptococcal Glomerulonephritis. 2022 Oct 9. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30855843.","Brant Pinheiro SV, de Freitas VB, de Castro GV, Rufino Madeiro BC, de Ara\u00fajo SA, Silva Ribeiro TF, Sim\u00f5es E Silva AC. Acute Post-Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis in Children: A Comprehensive Review. Curr Med Chem. 2022;29(34):5543-5559. doi: 10.2174/0929867329666220613103316. PMID: 35702785.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45565"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T10:57:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T10:58:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"d